a quantum diagonal map  
which on each function of  evaluates a state minimizing the
square Euclidean
length, while leaving the mean coordinates   invariant 
  (cf. , ).

As a consequence of taking the tensor product in () over , 
the mean coordinates  commute 
with the relative coordinates  (in the strong sense), e.g. for , 
 
This fact turns out to be crucial for the construction of the quantum
diagonal map and provides an additional motivation for taking the
tensor product over ,

Actually, the tensor product  of -moduli
can be defined as the completion relative to the maximal C*-seminorm of
the quotient of the algebraic tensor product over  modulo
the two sided ideal generated by the multiples in 
of , where  varies in . It may be equivalently
described as
the fibrewise tensor product of bundles of C*-algebras (continuous
fields of C*-algebras, in the terminology of) over
.

Another motivation to use a -module tensor product is to view the components
 of the coordinate's commutator as universal data which are
the same for the different variables corresponding to independent events. 
The s are thus treated as a point independent geometric 
background, which, however, is translation invariant and Lorentz covariant.

Since the C*-algebra  describes the regular representations of
(1), i.e. integrable to
a representation of the Weyl relations  






the uniqueness theorem of von Neumann , 
applied to each fibre at , ensures that
commutativity implies tensor factorization over . This fact will allow us
to obtain the desired map as a conditional expectation.

Furthermore,   we will use the tensor product of  copies of
the basic algebra as an auxiliary algebra, where the mean coordinates are
(affiliated to the algebra) in the first factor, and where 
the algebra to which the
difference variables  are affiliated is identified with a
subalgebra of the auxiliary algebra, associated to the factors from
