Time-ordering and Diagrammatics 


We complement our discussion with some formal remarks aiming to clarify the
relation between the approach followed here and the usual formulation of the
perturbation theory in terms of Feynman  diagrams.  We
have already shown in  
that the perturbative setup dealt with
in  (as well as the approach based on the Yang-Feldman equation) is
inequivalent to the  by now standard setup  in terms of the modified Feynman
rules . In this section we will make explicit that in the
framework of the regularized interaction proposed in this paper, Feynman
propagators are no more available at all.   

In this discussion we ignore all problems which may arise in the adiabatic
limit, and use the formal  (i.e. defined with constant coupling constant
)  time dependent
interaction Hamiltonian  throughout,




where the integral kernel  is of the form




and the Gaussian kernel  does not depend on .
Introducing the time ordered kernels







formal computations yield the formal Dyson expansion (see)
* 
where we use the notations (-).

By integrating over the time variables , we obtain
* 
Here 
is the ordering of the Wick monomials with respect to the average
time, i.e. the time of the mean position of each : more 
precisely, with
 
the time component of the four vector 
, 
we have
* 
where  can be
thought of as a "fat vertex",   i.e. a multi-vertex  
actually consisting of  Minkowski vectors.


The time ordering thus defined differs from the one discussed in . However, in both approaches causality is violated at
the Planck length scale   (cf. also ).
A typical manifestation of the violation of causality is the following:
suppose that  



 
i.e.
, then   it is not 
forbidden that  for some . 
In other words, a single field
 belonging to the first Wick monomial can be subsequent in time
to some field .


Note however, that the above picture is consistent with the request that the
large scale limit should reproduce the ordinary (non regularized) theory with
 interaction; in particular, as , the
multi-vertices shrink to their centres of mass, and the above average
time-ordering reduces to the usual one.


We conclude our discussion by showing that it is not possible to absorb the
time ordering in Feynman propagators, 
, as one usually does in the framework of
ordinary local theories. In fact, in the approach followed here, we cannot
construct Feynman propagators at all , while in the original Hamiltonian
approach based on () as well as in the approach based on the
Yang-Feldman equation it is still possible to rewrite the time ordering in
terms of Feynman propagators together with  advanced and retarded
propagators . 

To see what happens in the approach adopted here, 
consider as an example the second order contribution to the Dyson
series  with two internal contractions in quantum -interaction, as
depicted in figure . 
 
 
file=qfish.eps, height=3cm 

Multi-vertices are represented by the
points within a circle;  is the
average time of the multi-vertex , and the shadowed area
represents its causal completion.  

Here, the two multi-vertices are sets of four distinguishable points,


 and , and at most one
line originates from each of these points. A
kernel  belongs to each multi-vertex. The 
internal contractions lead to positive and negative frequency parts of the
commutator function,
, where . , while the
time ordering is done with respect to the time components of the mean
coordinates of each vertex, leading to the Heaviside functions
.
We may thus conclude that the distributions arising in the fish graph will not 
yield Feynman propagators at all. 

This is consistent with the fact that the usual interpretation of Feynman
graphs as pictorial representations of scattering processes ("first A is
annihilated, then B is created") should break down on quantum spacetime, as it
needs sharply localized events, which are no longer available. 


